# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1892-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1892-world-series/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] The 1871 season was the first season of the Boston Red Stockings franchise, now known as the Atlanta Braves.
[src:1892-world-series/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] They were formed in 1871 by Boston businessman and Ashburnham native Ivers Whitney Adams.
[src:1892-world-series/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] The team was composed of former players of the defunct Cincinnati Red Stockings franchise, who were brought to Boston and kept the name with them.
[src:1892-world-series/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Led and managed by baseball pioneer Harry Wright, the new Boston team would join the newly formed National Association of Professional Base Ball Players for the 1871 season and finish the year in third place with a record of 20–10.
[src:1892-world-series/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started all 31 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 19 wins.
[src:1892-world-series/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Catcher Cal McVey finished second in the league batting race with a .431 average.
[src:1892-world-series/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] From this team, Harry Wright, Al Spalding, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1892-world-series/1871-major-league-baseball-season] The tenth founding member, the National club of Washington, did not enter a team for the championship until 1872.
[src:1892-world-series/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1872 Boston Red Stockings season** was the second season of the franchise.
[src:1892-world-series/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] They won the National Association championship.
[src:1892-world-series/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 39–8 to win the pennant by 7.5 games.
[src:1892-world-series/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started all 48 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 38 wins.
[src:1892-world-series/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Second baseman Ross Barnes won the league batting title with a .430 batting average.
[src:1892-world-series/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1892-world-series/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1873 Boston Red Stockings season** was the third season of the franchise.
[src:1892-world-series/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their second consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1892-world-series/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 43–16 to win the pennant by 4 games.
[src:1892-world-series/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 54 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 41 wins.
[src:1892-world-series/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Second baseman Ross Barnes won the league batting title with a .431 batting average, and catcher Deacon White topped the circuit with 77 runs batted in.
[src:1892-world-series/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, first baseman Jim O'Rourke, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1892-world-series/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1874 Boston Red Stockings season** was the fourth season of the franchise.
[src:1892-world-series/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their third consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1892-world-series/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 52–18 to win the pennant by 7.5 games.
[src:1892-world-series/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 69 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 52 wins.
[src:1892-world-series/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Outfielder Cal McVey led the league with 71 runs batted in, and he paced the Boston offense which scored more runs than any other team.
[src:1892-world-series/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, first baseman Jim O'Rourke, catcher Deacon White, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1892-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1875 Boston Red Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Boston Red Stockings franchise.
[src:1892-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their fourth consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1892-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 71–8 to win the pennant by 15 games.
[src:1892-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 62 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 54 wins.
[src:1892-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Catcher Deacon White (.367), second baseman Ross Barnes (.364), and first baseman Cal McVey (.355) finished 1–2–3 in the league's batting race.
[src:1892-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] McVey paced the circuit with 87 runs batted in, and outfielder Jim O'Rourke had the most home runs, with 6.
[src:1892-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] The Boston offense scored more runs than any other team in the NA.
[src:1892-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, Jim O'Rourke, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1892-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] This was the last season of the Association, which dissolved at the end of the year.
[src:1892-world-series/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings club would join the new National League in 1876.
[src:1892-world-series/1876-boston-red-caps-season] The **1876 Boston Red Caps season** was the sixth season of the franchise.
[src:1892-world-series/1876-boston-red-caps-season] With the dissolution of the National Association, the Boston team joined the brand new National League.
[src:1892-world-series/1876-boston-red-caps-season] The team name was changed from the Boston Red Stockings to the **Boston Red Caps** to avoid confusion with the new Cincinnati Red Stockings team.
[src:1892-world-series/1876-boston-red-caps-season] Some of the players from the previous year's team defected to other ballclubs, so the team finished further down in the standings this season.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] The **1892 World Series** followed the first split season in National League history, with the first-half champion Boston Beaneaters (102–48) playing the second-half champion Cleveland Spiders (93–56) in a best-of-nine postseason series to determine the overall champion of the 1892 baseball season.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] After the first game ended in a 0–0 tie due to darkness, Boston won the next five games to win the championship.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] Contemporary newspaper reports referred to the games as the "**World's Championship Series**" or "**World's Series**".
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] This was the last of the pre-modern-era World Series, and followed similar annual postseason competitions held from 1884 to 1890 between the champions of the National League and the American Association (which collapsed after the 1891 season).
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] Later, the Temple Cup would be awarded to the winner of an annual postseason series between National League teams, from 1894 to 1897.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] Boston manager Frank Selee worried that late-October weather conditions would lead to postponements and low attendance.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] Bookies had the Spiders as the favorite, due to their pitching staff.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] Cy Young had gone 36–12 in 49 starts, with a 1.93 earned-run average.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] Meanwhile, Boston star Mike "King" Kelly had a batting average of only .189 for the year, and was described as "one of the biggest failures of the base ball season".
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] Hugh Duffy of Boston batted .462 with nine runs batted in and six extra-base hits including a home run.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] Had the series required more than six games to complete, the remaining games would have been played in New York City.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] The first game, which had started at three o'clock, had gone 11 scoreless innings when it was stopped at five o'clock due to darkness.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] After a travel day for the teams, the series moved to Boston with the Beaneaters leading, two games to none.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] John Clarkson started for Cleveland in place of Cy Young, who complained of a "lame arm".
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] After an off-day (professional baseball games were not allowed on Sundays in Boston until 1929) the Beaneaters won their fifth game of the series to capture the championship.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] The 13 players on their roster split $1000 prize money.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] The National League abolished the split season format for 1893, and did not play another split season until 1981, which was caused by a players' strike.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] John Clarkson had started the season with the Beaneaters, and signed with the Spiders after being released at the end of June.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] Pitcher Lee Viau also played for both Boston and Cleveland during 1892.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] The Beaneaters were later known as the Doves (1907–1910) and the Rustlers (1911) before adopting the nickname of "Braves" in 1912.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] The franchise relocated to Milwaukee in 1953, and then moved to Atlanta in 1966, where they remain members of the National League as the Atlanta Braves.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] The Spiders' final season was 1899, when they compiled a record of 20–134 (establishing a longstanding record for the worst major league season) after ownership moved their best players to the St.
[src:1892-world-series/1892-world-series] Louis Cardinals, and were one of four teams contracted out of the National League when the league reduced its size to eight teams prior to the 1900 season.
